<DOC><DOCNO> AP901120-0212 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-11-20-90 0723EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-HotDogRecall     11-20 0228</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Hot Dog Recall,0238</SECOND><HEAD>Chicago Company Recalls Hot Dogs Suspected Of Contamination</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: This was in PM-Washington in Brief on general news wires.</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Chicago company is recalling more than fivetons of hot dogs suspected of being contaminated by food poisoning.   Agriculture Department officials said on Monday that David Bergandamp; Co. is recalling 10,000 pounds of bulk-packed ``David Berg BeefFrankfurters'' distributed in California, Illinois, Massachusetts,Pennsylvania and Texas.   Also being recalled are about 1,400 pounds of retail-packaged``David Berg Deli Beef Franks'' distributed in the Chicagometropolitan area.   The franks may be contaminated with listeria monocytogenes, anorganism that can cause listeriosis, which was described as ``arare but potentially serious disease.'   The bulk-packed hot dogs are sold in 10-pound boxes and aredistributed to hot dog vendors, delicatessens and restaurants.``EST. 1'' appears inside the USDA inspection seal on the boxlabel. All bulk franks with the code 60250 on the bottom of the boxare being recalled.   The 12-ounce retail packages were distributed to grocery storesand supermarkets in Chicago. ``EST. 1'' appears in the inspectionseal on the package label. All retail packages with ``Sell by Dec.10'' stamped on the side of the package are being recalled.   None of the company's other products are involved in the recall,said Ronald J. Prucha, associate administrator of the department'sFood Safety and Inspection Service.</TEXT></DOC>